father was born here.

00:03:13.640 --> 00:03:17.980
My grandmother was born
in Texas and her mother--

00:03:17.980 --> 00:03:20.560
my great-grandmother-- and
my great-great-grandmother

00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:22.750
came to El Paso.

00:03:22.750 --> 00:03:27.580
They were Tarahumara
from Chihuahua.

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:30.520
And they were here
a long time ago.

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:37.940
My great-grandmother lived
in the Santa Clara Village

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:42.880
down on Virgil Street
near the metro station.

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:44.830
But my father was born here.

00:03:44.830 --> 00:03:46.090
His mother was born here.

00:03:46.090 --> 00:03:48.890
He was repatriated to Mexico.

00:03:48.890 --> 00:03:52.450
His father went with
him-- my grandfather.

00:03:52.450 --> 00:03:57.580
And I found the paperwork
of my grandfather, who

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:04.000
was Apache, living on a
reservation in Arizona

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:05.170
and working there.

00:04:05.170 --> 00:04:09.850
And his registration for
the draft for World War I--

00:04:09.850 --> 00:04:11.020
I find this, right?

00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:11.950
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Wow.

00:04:11.950 --> 00:04:14.320
MARGARET GARCIA: And yet,
he's repatriated along

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:16.540
with my father and
his two brothers.

00:04:16.540 --> 00:04:25.720
And his eldest brother drowns on
the trip back through Tijuana.

00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:30.070
He absconded with the children
and then was repatriated,

00:04:30.070 --> 00:04:37.960
and so he was
raised near ObregÃ³n,

00:04:37.960 --> 00:04:41.860
Sonora in a little
[INAUDIBLE] village.

00:04:41.860 --> 00:04:46.690
You know, he was Apache,
but you know the thing

00:04:46.690 --> 00:04:49.270
that I think a lot
of Americans do not

00:04:49.270 --> 00:04:53.050
understand about the
Mexican experience--

00:04:53.050 --> 00:04:55.090
the Chicano
experience-- because I'm

00:04:55.090 --> 00:04:56.800
sort of that subset of group.

00:04:56.800 --> 00:04:58.690
I'm Chicana, you know.

00:04:58.690 --> 00:05:05.350
--is that he's Apache, and
the Yaqui and the Apache

00:05:05.350 --> 00:05:07.270
are kind of like family.

00:05:07.270 --> 00:05:11.450
They're like different
clans of the same people.

00:05:11.450 --> 00:05:14.770
And one of the
reasons why we hold on

00:05:14.770 --> 00:05:20.710
so dearly to the terminology
of that-- and other Latinos

00:05:20.710 --> 00:05:24.040
don't understand it
because they say, well,

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:25.240
but you're not including us.

00:05:25.240 --> 00:05:26.950
It isn't that we want
to exclude people.

00:05:26.950 --> 00:05:33.520
I think we are very
inclusive, but the terminology

00:05:33.520 --> 00:05:38.920
that links us to this land
continually and perpetually

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:43.120
makes us the immigrant,
whether we are or we are not.

00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:44.440
And my father was born here.

00:05:44.440 --> 00:05:46.040
His mother was born here.

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:50.110
They're from indigenous people
who are from this continent.

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:52.510
We are not really
the immigrant, but we

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:55.180
are the perpetual immigrant.

00:05:55.180 --> 00:05:58.270
And that's something that
people do not understand.

00:05:58.270 --> 00:06:00.970
And it's one of the reasons
why people like me--

00:06:00.970 --> 00:06:03.730
born in the '50s--

00:06:03.730 --> 00:06:06.850
people call me Chicanosaurus or
whatever they want to call me.

00:06:06.850 --> 00:06:08.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:08.350 --> 00:06:09.559
I'm good with that, you know.

00:06:09.559 --> 00:06:11.683
MARCUS GRIMALDO: It's the
first I've heard of that,

00:06:11.683 --> 00:06:12.490
but I love it.

00:06:12.490 --> 00:06:14.365
MARGARET GARCIA: Yeah,
you know, stuck in it,

00:06:14.365 --> 00:06:19.360
but that's fine for me
because I understand

00:06:19.360 --> 00:06:21.640
how important that
piece of heritage

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:25.060
is to us because
Mexicanos-- all of them--

00:06:25.060 --> 00:06:26.950
they're not all immigrants.

00:06:26.950 --> 00:06:32.020
And California-- and I
did the metro station

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:36.550
at the Campo de Cahuenga where
the capitulation of Cahuenga

00:06:36.550 --> 00:06:41.800
was signed making California a
territory of the United States.

00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:44.360
This was Mexico, people.

00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:48.250
So that's really difficult
for people to understand,

00:06:48.250 --> 00:06:50.830
but it's a very,
very deep heritage.

00:06:50.830 --> 00:06:54.370
And yes, we have a
lot of connections

00:06:54.370 --> 00:06:57.250
with the rest of the
Latinos of Central

00:06:57.250 --> 00:07:00.770
and South America
and everything else,

00:07:00.770 --> 00:07:02.312
but I can't give that up yet.

00:07:02.312 --> 00:07:03.770
MARCUS GRIMALDO:
No, you know what?

00:07:03.770 --> 00:07:06.140
And I completely
