00:12:57.839 --> 00:12:59.130
was looking for a piece of art.

00:12:59.130 --> 00:13:01.800
You know, there's
the 1% for art,

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:03.990
and myself, and
two other artists.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:12.780
It was for a location
that dealt with mariachis.

00:13:12.780 --> 00:13:18.420
And I said, well, you
need to honor musicians.

00:13:18.420 --> 00:13:21.160
And I thought of two people.

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:25.170
And the first one was Selena.

00:13:25.170 --> 00:13:27.780
The second person
was Lalo Guerrero,

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:34.980
but I really wanted a woman
because oftentimes, there's

00:13:34.980 --> 00:13:35.970
not as many of us.

00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:37.954
You know what I mean.

00:13:37.954 --> 00:13:40.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:40.290 --> 00:13:44.680
So you know it's important
to support the women.

00:13:44.680 --> 00:13:47.340
And she's beautiful.

00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:50.640
She's from Texas where
my grandmother is from.

00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:54.030
So I thought she's the one.

00:13:54.030 --> 00:13:58.320
She's the one that I need to
honor in this particular way.

00:14:01.020 --> 00:14:03.900
I can't dig her up and
ask her to sit for me.

00:14:03.900 --> 00:14:08.610
I only have the images
that exist of her

00:14:08.610 --> 00:14:09.800
as they exist of her.

00:14:09.800 --> 00:14:14.670
So it was about me
reinterpreting them and trying

00:14:14.670 --> 00:14:17.190
to make it look like a
stained glass window.

00:14:17.190 --> 00:14:19.010
And the thing about
stained glass windows

00:14:19.010 --> 00:14:23.790
is there's always a
sense of sacredness.

00:14:23.790 --> 00:14:27.670
It's a spiritual experience.

00:14:27.670 --> 00:14:31.037
And so that's what I went for.

00:14:31.037 --> 00:14:32.370
MARCUS GRIMALDO: That's amazing.

00:14:32.370 --> 00:14:34.140
I mean, I got
chills looking at it

00:14:34.140 --> 00:14:35.799
because it's just so fantastic.

00:14:35.799 --> 00:14:36.840
And I think you're right.

00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:38.040
I think that's what it was.

00:14:38.040 --> 00:14:40.350
It was like there's
something familiar about it.

00:14:40.350 --> 00:14:43.950
I didn't quite know how
to put the pulse on it,

00:14:43.950 --> 00:14:45.290
but I think you hit it.

00:14:45.290 --> 00:14:46.290
It's very sacred.

00:14:46.290 --> 00:14:49.530
You know, you see that
and now that's fantastic.

00:14:49.530 --> 00:14:51.360
Now, you mentioned
there's three of them.

00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:53.070
We had a chance to
talk before, right?

00:14:53.070 --> 00:14:54.153
And you did three of them.

00:14:54.153 --> 00:14:55.154
This was the biggest.

00:14:55.154 --> 00:14:56.070
Who has the other two?

00:14:56.070 --> 00:14:56.700
Can you share?

00:14:56.700 --> 00:14:56.970
MARGARET GARCIA: I do.

00:14:56.970 --> 00:14:58.170
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Oh, you do.

00:14:58.170 --> 00:15:00.850
OK, who are you saving them for?

00:15:00.850 --> 00:15:02.262
I want one.

00:15:02.262 --> 00:15:03.720
MARGARET GARCIA:
They're different.

00:15:03.720 --> 00:15:07.200
Each one is a little different.

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:10.320
The other two are
done in steel boxes.

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:15.000
So I actually try to show
it in the dark instead

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.390
of trying to light it because
the light comes from the back,

00:15:19.390 --> 00:15:23.935
and so you don't need to
light it because it glows.

00:15:23.935 --> 00:15:24.810
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Wow.

00:15:24.810 --> 00:15:27.660
MARGARET GARCIA: So the boxes
were intended to do that,

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:30.390
but then I found
this other person

00:15:30.390 --> 00:15:35.160
who started talking to me about
shattered plate glass windows.

00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:39.360
And he was a glass guy and
he talked about the effect.

00:15:39.360 --> 00:15:41.640
And he said that I could--

00:15:41.640 --> 00:15:49.110
it's called I want to say cold
bonding or cold laminating.

00:15:49.110 --> 00:15:50.100
There's a process.

00:15:50.100 --> 00:15:52.080
So he walked me
through that and so

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:54.570
I put the shattered
glass on the outside.

00:15:54.570 --> 00:15:57.480
It makes it tough to
handle, but you're not

00:15:57.480 --> 00:15:58.900
supposed to handle it.

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:01.620
So if you've got your hands
on my art, take them off.

00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:02.542
You'll get cut.

00:16:02.542 --> 00:16:03.750
MARCUS GRIMALDO: No touching.

00:16:03.750 --> 00:16:05.100
MARGARET GARCIA: No touching
because you will get cut.

00:16:05.100 --> 00:16:06.225
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Only look.

00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:13.470
And then lastly, this is
just one representation

00:16:13.470 --> 00:16:16.287
of what she does by the way.

00:16:16.287 --> 00:16:18.120
There's other forms of
expression or artwork

00:16:18.120 --> 00:16:18.570
that you have.

00:16:18.570 --> 00:16:20.778
Do you want to just kind of
give us a little bit more

00:16:20.778 --> 00:16:21.720
insight to that?

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:25.100
We will have this also posted
on our websites as well locally,

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:26.910
so for the rest
of the folks that

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:30.075
are watching that are here, stay
tuned because that is to come.

00:16:30.075 --> 00:16:31.560
But I want you to
kind of give us

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:34.770
a little sneak peek
into what to expect.

00:16:34.770 --> 00:16:37.140
MARGARET GARCIA:
Well, I've done a lot

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:40.240
of portraits in the beginning.

00:16:40.240 --> 00:16:42.540
And one of the reasons
I've done portraits

00:16:42.540 --> 00:16:46.770
is because I felt it was
important for my community

00:16:46.770 --> 00:16:50.740
to define ourselves from within
and not be defined by what

00:16:50.740 --> 00:16:53.020
the media wants to call us.

00:16:53.020 --> 00:16:57.400
So if you see
yourself in the media

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:01.750
and you're maybe a gardener,
a housekeeper, a gangbanger,

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:03.430
or any of the other
negative things

00:17:03.430 --> 00:17:08.470
that I care not to repeat, and
they're talking ill about you,

00:17:08.470 --> 00:17:10.990
part of that is because
other people are defining you

00:17:10.990 --> 00:17:12.910
and they don't know who you are.

00:17:12.910 --> 00:17:15.670
They don't know us.

00:17:15.670 --> 00:17:19.660
They don't know us if they think
that we're those things that

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:22.089
have been repeated by 45.

00:17:22.089 --> 00:17:23.859
The only thing I can say is--

00:17:26.605 --> 00:17:29.080
my brother is sitting in
the audience right now.

00:17:29.080 --> 00:17:31.000
He's a doctor.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:32.890
He's a trauma surgeon.

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:35.440
We are people who have
accomplished things.

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:40.420
We are people who have done
things and have contributed.

00:17:40.420 --> 00:17:44.830
Whether you're talking about
science, innovation, medicine,

00:17:44.830 --> 00:17:50.735
arts, we're here and we are
part of the American fabric.

00:17:50.735 --> 00:17:51.860
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Thank you.

00:17:51.860 --> 00:17:53.010
Thank you.

00:17:53.010 --> 00:17:55.260
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:56.160 --> 00:18:00.124
All right, Manuel Lopez.

00:18:00.124 --> 00:18:02.040
Sorry, you know, her
story was so good it made

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:03.792
your back pop off, didn't it?

00:18:03.792 --> 00:18:04.955
MANUEL LOPEZ: Yeah, it did.

00:18:04.955 --> 00:18:06.330
MARCUS GRIMALDO:
It felt it, huh?

00:18:06.330 --> 00:18:08.070
The chair even felt it.

00:18:08.070 --> 00:18:11.850
Sorry about that, but so
glad to have you here.

00:18:11.850 --> 00:18:14.160
Manuel Lopez--
another Angeleno--

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:17.520
grew up in East Los Angeles.

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:18.510
I read your story.

00:18:18.510 --> 00:18:20.806
I don't want to talk too much
because I want to hear it

00:18:20.806 --> 00:18:22.680
from you, but it's so
funny because as a kid,

00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:26.460
it started with a
competition with his sister

00:18:26.460 --> 00:18:30.120
on a who could draw the
better Trix rabbit--

00:18:30.120 --> 00:18:31.620
bunny rabbit.

00:18:31.620 --> 00:18:33.600
And then he ran with
that and he ended up

00:18:33.600 --> 00:18:35.190
getting so excited
about "Mario Kart"

00:18:35.190 --> 00:18:38.130
that he painted his whole TV
at his home at eight years old,

00:18:38.130 --> 00:18:39.420
I believe--

00:18:39.420 --> 00:18:42.030
the whole TV as a Mario canvas.

00:18:42.030 --> 00:18:45.430
Mom was not happy.

00:18:45.430 --> 00:18:47.620
And then he's been around.

00:18:47.620 --> 00:18:49.450
He attended East
Los Angeles college.

00:18:49.450 --> 00:18:53.540
He transferred to the School of
the Art Institute of Chicago.

00:18:53.540 --> 00:18:55.720
And he was featured in
the "LA Times" article.

00:18:55.720 --> 00:18:58.060
And that must have been a
big, big moment for you.

00:18:58.060 --> 00:19:00.310
So ladies and gentlemen,
let's give him a warm welcome

00:19:00.310 --> 00:19:02.305
of applause and let's
get to know him.

00:19:02.305 --> 00:19:03.520
[APPLAUSE]

00:19:03.520 --> 00:19:04.645
MANUEL LOPEZ: Thank you.

00:19:04.645 --> 00:19:06.270
MARCUS GRIMALDO: So
Manuel, talk to me.

00:19:06.270 --> 00:19:08.936
I kind of gave us the low down--
a little bit about who you are.

00:19:08.936 --> 00:19:11.440
But I mean, I look
at your artwork

00:19:11.440 --> 00:19:12.760
and what you've done here.

00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:17.125
And I was telling, I think it
was you as a matter of fact--

00:19:17.125 --> 00:19:18.000
no, Nilza, excuse me.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:21.834
I was telling Nilza, who is
our business partner here

00:19:21.834 --> 00:19:23.500
and facilitated the
artists coming here,

00:19:23.500 --> 00:19:24.400
so thank you so much.

00:19:24.400 --> 00:19:26.900
We had a chance to talk, and
I said I feel like this is--

00:19:26.900 --> 00:19:30.070
the artwork brings
us kind of here

00:19:30.070 --> 00:19:31.700
and there at the same time.

00:19:31.700 --> 00:19:34.000
And when I mean that, the
East Los Angeles landscape,

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:38.230
but it's very reminiscent of
Mexico, at least that's what

00:19:38.230 --> 00:19:39.800
I get from this expression.

00:19:39.800 --> 00:19:44.050
So talk to me about growing
up, how this became something

00:19:44.050 --> 00:19:48.580
for you, what you've done,
all the accomplishments you've

00:19:48.580 --> 00:19:50.320
done with the Los
Angeles article,

00:19:50.320 --> 00:19:53.530
and then where
you plan on going.

00:19:53.530 --> 00:19:55.370
MANUEL LOPEZ: Well,
I guess I started

00:19:55.370 --> 00:19:58.660
drawing when I was
very young, I mean,

00:19:58.660 --> 00:20:02.002
as far as back as
I can remember.

00:20:02.002 --> 00:20:03.460
That was a very
vivid memory that I

00:20:03.460 --> 00:20:06.840
have from my childhood when I
used to compete with my sister.

00:20:06.840 --> 00:20:09.580
It was just for the fun of it.

00:20:09.580 --> 00:20:12.260
I guess my dad will
get a kick out of it.

00:20:12.260 --> 00:20:16.420
So I mean, I always
realize that drawing came

00:20:16.420 --> 00:20:19.390
more easy than with other kids.

00:20:19.390 --> 00:20:22.980
So it was just-- it
came really easy.

00:20:22.980 --> 00:20:27.016
I could just see things
and just put them on paper.

00:20:27.016 --> 00:20:28.390
I never really
took it seriously.

00:20:28.390 --> 00:20:30.250
It was always a game to me.

00:20:30.250 --> 00:20:34.480
I mean, I just really
enjoyed doing it.

00:20:34.480 --> 00:20:36.910
I grew up in Boyle Heights.

00:20:36.910 --> 00:20:40.750
And then at about age,
I think, eight or nine,

00:20:40.750 --> 00:20:44.650
we moved to East LA.

00:20:44.650 --> 00:20:49.630
And I remember, like, moving
the stuff from our old house

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:51.160
to our new house in East LA.

00:20:51.160 --> 00:20:53.740
And I remember looking at
the City Terrace hills.

00:20:53.740 --> 00:20:55.159
And they just left--

00:20:55.159 --> 00:20:56.950
I don't know, I just
saw them and I thought

00:20:56.950 --> 00:20:58.350
they looked really beautiful.

00:21:01.940 --> 00:21:06.680
Night came, and the
sun was just setting,

00:21:06.680 --> 00:21:11.150
and the lights were turning on.

00:21:11.150 --> 00:21:14.480
And I remember saying like,
wow, can this get any better?

00:21:14.480 --> 00:21:16.260
It was to me, it just
really spoke to me.

00:21:16.260 --> 00:21:18.770
And then I started thinking
about the people who

00:21:18.770 --> 00:21:20.870
lived up there.

00:21:20.870 --> 00:21:23.540
And so I left it at that
for a really long time.

00:21:23.540 --> 00:21:27.660
I kept making drawings
after drawing after drawing.

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:32.340
This was from when I
was about 10 to 18.

00:21:32.340 --> 00:21:35.620
I never took an art
class in high school.

00:21:35.620 --> 00:21:40.550
Well, I went over to ELAC,
met some good people there--

00:21:40.550 --> 00:21:43.940
a good instructor by
the name of Jim Uyekawa.

00:21:43.940 --> 00:21:49.850
And he just started to put
the idea in me that it's fun,

00:21:49.850 --> 00:21:52.070
but also it takes a discipline.

00:21:52.070 --> 00:21:55.290
It takes discipline, and it
takes time, and it takes work.

00:21:55.290 --> 00:21:59.540
And I was 18, so I didn't
take it too seriously.

00:21:59.540 --> 00:22:03.730
You know, like I would
still goof around,

00:22:03.730 --> 00:22:05.060
but I still kept at it.

00:22:05.060 --> 00:22:10.820
And luckily, a couple years
after I enrolled at ELAC,

00:22:10.820 --> 00:22:12.890
I put a portfolio
together and I got

00:22:12.890 --> 00:22:17.240
accepted to the School of
the Art Institute of Chicago.

00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:18.740
I had done some research.

00:22:18.740 --> 00:22:22.940
I was checking for major
schools that were in the US.

00:22:22.940 --> 00:22:25.970
I looked at Rhode
Island School of Design.

00:22:25.970 --> 00:22:29.510
I looked at the School of
the Art Institute of Chicago.

00:22:29.510 --> 00:22:31.020
Then I took a trip out there.

00:22:31.020 --> 00:22:33.260
I visited both campuses.

00:22:33.260 --> 00:22:37.670
And the School of the Art
Institute by far was, I mean,

00:22:37.670 --> 00:22:41.510
they just had this beautiful
collection of all sorts of art.

00:22:41.510 --> 00:22:45.140
And to be able to look at
it while studying, I think

00:22:45.140 --> 00:22:52.027
was definitely like a prize
because I love to look at art.

00:22:52.027 --> 00:22:53.110
I mean, I love to make it.

00:22:53.110 --> 00:22:56.555
I like to look at it as well.

00:22:56.555 --> 00:22:57.510
What else?

00:22:57.510 --> 00:22:59.780
MARCUS GRIMALDO: So if we
were looking at these three

00:22:59.780 --> 00:23:03.080
paintings here, how
does that come about?

00:23:03.080 --> 00:23:04.190
What's the inspiration?

00:23:04.190 --> 00:23:07.160
I know you mentioned it seems
like landscape is definitely

00:23:07.160 --> 00:23:11.090
at the forefront of how you
envision things, and what

00:23:11.090 --> 00:23:13.040
inspires you, and what
compels you, right?

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:16.970
So when you start with the
landscape and the vision,

00:23:16.970 --> 00:23:18.080
what's that process like?

00:23:18.080 --> 00:23:19.880
For us that aren't
artists that don't know,

00:23:19.880 --> 00:23:22.010
but that are super
excited and they're like,

00:23:22.010 --> 00:23:25.670
how does something so
simple and beautiful happen?

00:23:25.670 --> 00:23:27.290
And is it as easy as it looks?

00:23:27.290 --> 00:23:28.970
Is it harder?

00:23:28.970 --> 00:23:31.442
Educate us a little bit on that
process, if you don't mind.

00:23:31.442 --> 00:23:32.900
MANUEL LOPEZ: Well,
these paintings

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:35.240
were started off as-- they
started off as drawings.

00:23:35.240 --> 00:23:37.700
I usually always work on-site.

00:23:37.700 --> 00:23:41.647
I take paper, pencil, and
I spend a couple of times--

00:23:41.647 --> 00:23:43.730
I don't mean a couple of
times-- a couple of hours

00:23:43.730 --> 00:23:44.780
up on the hillside.

00:23:47.350 --> 00:23:50.810
I mean, I think it's very
meditative to just sit out

00:23:50.810 --> 00:23:54.200
there by yourself, and you're
confronting the whole landscape

00:23:54.200 --> 00:23:57.300
in front of you, and you
know that you're part of it,

00:23:57.300 --> 00:23:59.471
and you're looking
at these houses which

00:23:59.471 --> 00:24:03.890
hold people that
are contributing

00:24:03.890 --> 00:24:07.790
to the American society.

00:24:07.790 --> 00:24:11.690
And so just like Margaret
said that our lives are not

00:24:11.690 --> 00:24:12.650
in the media--

00:24:12.650 --> 00:24:14.190
in the popular media--

00:24:14.190 --> 00:24:16.160
you know, I mean, those
houses hold everything

00:24:16.160 --> 00:24:19.610
from the gangster
to the mechanic that

00:24:19.610 --> 00:24:22.550
works 80 hours a week.

00:24:22.550 --> 00:24:26.510
And just being up there
as the sun is setting,

00:24:26.510 --> 00:24:29.540
those hills just come alive.

00:24:29.540 --> 00:24:31.257
You get people
coming in from work.

00:24:31.257 --> 00:24:32.840
You have kids running
down the street.

00:24:32.840 --> 00:24:36.460
You have the paletero
selling his stuff.

00:24:36.460 --> 00:24:40.310
You have the paisas coming
along with the Chalino blasting.

00:24:40.310 --> 00:24:43.807
And you smell the carne asada
and it just it feels good.

00:24:43.807 --> 00:24:44.640
It feels, you know--

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:47.360
and I'm part of it, you know.

00:24:47.360 --> 00:24:48.370
When I look at them--

00:24:48.370 --> 00:24:50.078
like a lot of people
have been telling me

00:24:50.078 --> 00:24:53.270
that it reminds them of Mexico,
but I mean, I've been to Mexico

00:24:53.270 --> 00:24:55.860
and it doesn't really
remind me of Mexico.

00:24:55.860 --> 00:24:58.370
But I mean, to each his own.

00:24:58.370 --> 00:25:02.900
But I mean, I think
when I'm making this,

00:25:02.900 --> 00:25:07.050
I'm aware that I come
from Southern California

00:25:07.050 --> 00:25:09.800
and I love--

00:25:09.800 --> 00:25:12.810
I came across David Hockney's
work some years ago.

00:25:12.810 --> 00:25:14.870
And I love the way
he captures light.

00:25:14.870 --> 00:25:18.410
And so I'm aware that I
come from that tradition.

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:20.270
Even though he's
from England, he

00:25:20.270 --> 00:25:24.140
landed in Southern California
and he made Southern California

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:25.847
his playground.

00:25:25.847 --> 00:25:27.680
I'm looking at other
artists like Ed Ruscha.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:31.520
I'm looking at the
artists that I couldn't

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:35.120
see when I was younger because
I was walking on the streets

00:25:35.120 --> 00:25:38.090
and I would see a
mural by Frank Romero.

00:25:38.090 --> 00:25:40.730
I would see a mural
by David Botello.

00:25:40.730 --> 00:25:45.630
So in a way, like
when I saw Hockney,

00:25:45.630 --> 00:25:47.370
it was something new for me.

00:25:47.370 --> 00:25:52.070
So these guys right here,
I think more than anything,

00:25:52.070 --> 00:25:53.570
I think they're
Southern California.

00:25:53.570 --> 00:25:55.340
I think they're
Southern California.

00:25:55.340 --> 00:25:57.290
I'm trying to capture the sun.

00:25:57.290 --> 00:26:02.540
I'm trying to capture
the palm trees, I think.

00:26:02.540 --> 00:26:05.460
I think just when you
look at the landscape,

00:26:05.460 --> 00:26:11.530
I think I get excited by looking
at all the different trees,

00:26:11.530 --> 00:26:13.340
at all the different life forms.

00:26:13.340 --> 00:26:16.460
This is their environment and
we're part of it, you know.

00:26:16.460 --> 00:26:17.030
MARCUS GRIMALDO:
Yeah, I love that.

00:26:17.030 --> 00:26:18.710
It's like you said it
was meditative to you.

00:26:18.710 --> 00:26:21.110
I think it's very therapeutic
for us here just listening

00:26:21.110 --> 00:26:21.610
to that.

00:26:21.610 --> 00:26:25.100
And then even more exciting
and honorable on your behalf

00:26:25.100 --> 00:26:28.610
is that you're representing that
community to the fullest in one

00:26:28.610 --> 00:26:30.084
of the most unique ways.

00:26:30.084 --> 00:26:31.500
Like, not everybody
could do that,

00:26:31.500 --> 00:26:33.662
so that's absolutely fantastic.

00:26:33.662 --> 00:26:34.620
I want to switch gears.

00:26:34.620 --> 00:26:36.680
I do want to talk about
the "LA Times" article.

00:26:36.680 --> 00:26:38.360
I think that's a
huge accomplishment.

00:26:38.360 --> 00:26:39.520
I had a chance--

00:26:39.520 --> 00:26:42.210
an opportunity to read
it multiple times.

00:26:42.210 --> 00:26:43.290
How did that happen?

00:26:43.290 --> 00:26:44.180
Did you expect that?

00:26:44.180 --> 00:26:47.870
Did you ever think that at
this time in your career,

00:26:47.870 --> 00:26:48.560
it would happen?

00:26:48.560 --> 00:26:52.160
I mean, you seem pretty young,
so that's a big accomplishment

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:54.260
to get that visibility,
that presence.

00:26:54.260 --> 00:26:55.010
That's awesome.

00:26:55.010 --> 00:26:57.200
And again, you are
the LA story, right?

00:26:57.200 --> 00:27:00.005
And so what better
way to have somebody

00:27:00.005 --> 00:27:02.630
highlight that and showcase than
the "LA Times" article, right?

00:27:02.630 --> 00:27:05.220
So can you talk us
through that journey,

00:27:05.220 --> 00:27:07.340
and how it happened,
when it happened,

00:27:07.340 --> 00:27:09.830
what does it mean, has
it been impactful for you

00:27:09.830 --> 00:27:10.580
as an artist--

00:27:10.580 --> 00:27:11.090
your career?

00:27:12.720 --> 00:27:14.900
MANUEL LOPEZ: So the
story came about like,

00:27:14.900 --> 00:27:18.500
I usually like, kick it with
friends that are into the arts.

00:27:18.500 --> 00:27:20.420
Like, they do
photography or they drum.

00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:24.950
And we go hit up the hills.

00:27:24.950 --> 00:27:27.346
We'll go up there for
a couple of hours.

00:27:27.346 --> 00:27:28.970
And then one of them
is a photographer.

00:27:28.970 --> 00:27:31.700
His name is Rafael Cardenas.

00:27:31.700 --> 00:27:34.160
And he tells me one day, hey,
let me follow you around.

00:27:34.160 --> 00:27:37.070
Let me, you know, just
pretend I'm not even there.

00:27:37.070 --> 00:27:38.250
You do your thing.

00:27:38.250 --> 00:27:40.434
And I'll try to stay
out of your way.

00:27:40.434 --> 00:27:41.600
And I'm like, well, fuck it.

00:27:41.600 --> 00:27:42.630
Let's do it.

00:27:42.630 --> 00:27:44.270
So we went up.

00:27:44.270 --> 00:27:47.910
He followed me around for
maybe like about seven hours.

00:27:47.910 --> 00:27:48.980
You know?

00:27:48.980 --> 00:27:51.950
We hit up three different
spots in City Terrace.

00:27:51.950 --> 00:27:54.950
No, two spots in City
Terrace, one in Elysian Park.

00:27:54.950 --> 00:27:57.599
So we went around.

00:27:57.599 --> 00:27:59.015
He said, like,
hey, man, I'm going

00:27:59.015 --> 00:28:01.610
to do like a little video
montage of everything

00:28:01.610 --> 00:28:02.929
I captured.

00:28:02.929 --> 00:28:03.970
I'm like, go for it, man.

00:28:03.970 --> 00:28:05.636
Just make me look--
you know, look good.

00:28:05.636 --> 00:28:06.410
You know?

00:28:06.410 --> 00:28:08.400
So he's like, dude, I
don't promise anything.

00:28:08.400 --> 00:28:08.900
You know?

00:28:08.900 --> 00:28:10.945
And I'm like, no, I'm
just messing around, man.

00:28:10.945 --> 00:28:12.070
Do whatever you need to do.

00:28:12.070 --> 00:28:14.130
And he-- you know, he--

00:28:14.130 --> 00:28:15.597
a couple months pass.

00:28:15.597 --> 00:28:16.930
I didn't hear anything from him.

00:28:16.930 --> 00:28:20.050
And then like, out of the blue,
he tells me, you know what?

00:28:20.050 --> 00:28:22.900
I'm done with the editing.

00:28:22.900 --> 00:28:25.150
And if you want to check
it out, come through.

00:28:25.150 --> 00:28:25.942
I stopped by.

00:28:25.942 --> 00:28:26.650
I checked it out.

00:28:26.650 --> 00:28:27.358
I was like, damn.

00:28:27.358 --> 00:28:28.870
Like, I was--

00:28:28.870 --> 00:28:31.330
I think the way he just
filmed everything was really,

00:28:31.330 --> 00:28:34.480
it was amazing.

00:28:34.480 --> 00:28:39.460
There was beautiful music in the
background by some guy, Arenas.

00:28:39.460 --> 00:28:42.310
I don't know if you guys
have heard of Chicano Batman?

00:28:42.310 --> 00:28:43.230
Yeah, so he goes--

00:28:43.230 --> 00:28:44.380
MARCUS GRIMALDO:
I'm hearing some--

00:28:44.380 --> 00:28:45.255
yeah, so [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:45.255 --> 00:28:46.390
I gotta check him out.

00:28:46.390 --> 00:28:48.750
MANUEL LOPEZ: He did
the background music

00:28:48.750 --> 00:28:50.890
and beautifully composed.

00:28:50.890 --> 00:28:51.700
You know?

00:28:51.700 --> 00:28:53.240
He puts it on his website.

00:28:53.240 --> 00:28:55.247
And I'm like, OK,
that's cool, you know?

00:28:55.247 --> 00:28:56.080
Like, I was really--

00:28:56.080 --> 00:28:56.913
I was happy for him.

00:28:56.913 --> 00:29:01.900
Because it was his first
like editing video.

00:29:01.900 --> 00:29:05.950
Because he's usually
shooting photos.

00:29:05.950 --> 00:29:10.180
And so a couple of weeks
after he puts it online,

00:29:10.180 --> 00:29:12.880
I get a call from my girlfriend.

00:29:12.880 --> 00:29:14.510
And she tells me, you know what?

00:29:14.510 --> 00:29:16.270
Like, Rafael just called me up.

00:29:16.270 --> 00:29:19.199
And he tells me to tell
you to check your email.

00:29:19.199 --> 00:29:20.240
I don't have a cellphone.

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:22.750
I've been cellphone-free
for about seven years.

00:29:22.750 --> 00:29:23.875
MARCUS GRIMALDO: I'm sorry?

00:29:23.875 --> 00:29:25.650
Wait, can you say
that one more--

00:29:25.650 --> 00:29:27.416
wait, did I hear that correctly?

00:29:27.416 --> 00:29:28.540
You don't have a cellphone?

00:29:28.540 --> 00:29:30.657
And you haven't had a
cellphone for seven years?

00:29:30.657 --> 00:29:31.740
MANUEL LOPEZ: Seven years.

00:29:31.740 --> 00:29:32.630
Yeah.

00:29:32.630 --> 00:29:35.320
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Wow.

00:29:35.320 --> 00:29:38.110
MANUEL LOPEZ: So every time
people want to contact me--

00:29:38.110 --> 00:29:39.490
MARCUS GRIMALDO: They've got
to go through the girlfriend.

00:29:39.490 --> 00:29:40.780
MANUEL LOPEZ: I
don't even know, man.

00:29:40.780 --> 00:29:42.154
I don't know how
they do it, man.

00:29:42.154 --> 00:29:43.727
It's pretty amazing.

00:29:43.727 --> 00:29:44.810
They get to track me down.

00:29:44.810 --> 00:29:45.310
You know?

00:29:45.310 --> 00:29:47.770
But anyways, so
I check my email.

00:29:47.770 --> 00:29:52.395
And then I read the email from,
her name is Esmeralda Bermudez.

00:29:52.395 --> 00:29:55.270
And she tells me, you
know, I saw Rafael's video.

00:29:55.270 --> 00:29:57.430
And I was wondering if
I could interview you

00:29:57.430 --> 00:29:59.590
for a future piece.

00:29:59.590 --> 00:30:02.200
And at first, I didn't
know what to think.

00:30:02.200 --> 00:30:04.836
Because I was like,
wow, the "LA Times."

00:30:04.836 --> 00:30:07.630
So I'm like, well, yeah,
let's make it happen.

00:30:07.630 --> 00:30:09.300
She hits me up.

00:30:09.300 --> 00:30:10.450
We go to the local cafe.

00:30:10.450 --> 00:30:12.350
She interviews me
for about two hours.

00:30:12.350 --> 00:30:13.264
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Wow.

00:30:13.264 --> 00:30:14.930
MANUEL LOPEZ: I'm
like, OK, that's cool.

00:30:14.930 --> 00:30:16.300
We went into it.

00:30:16.300 --> 00:30:17.000
We spoke.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:17.890
We had lunch.

00:30:17.890 --> 00:30:20.576
We drank coffee.

00:30:20.576 --> 00:30:22.450
And then she's like,
oh, this is really good.

00:30:22.450 --> 00:30:23.450
When can we do it again?

00:30:23.450 --> 00:30:25.120
So I'm like, what the fuck?

00:30:25.120 --> 00:30:26.371
Dude, we did two hours.

00:30:26.371 --> 00:30:27.370
And then she wants more?

00:30:27.370 --> 00:30:29.590
I'm like, let's do it next week.

00:30:29.590 --> 00:30:31.480
And she's like, all right.

00:30:31.480 --> 00:30:33.190
And then we do that.

00:30:33.190 --> 00:30:34.930
And then again, hey,
let's do it again.

00:30:34.930 --> 00:30:36.400
I'm like, dang.

00:30:36.400 --> 00:30:36.940
All right.

00:30:36.940 --> 00:30:38.440
So two more hours
and then I don't

00:30:38.440 --> 00:30:39.610
know how many times we met.

00:30:39.610 --> 00:30:41.440
But it was just really good.

00:30:41.440 --> 00:30:42.507
Like it was--

00:30:42.507 --> 00:30:44.590
I guess the word I want
to use is kind of therapy.

00:30:44.590 --> 00:30:48.190
Because she was really trying
to go deep into the practice

00:30:48.190 --> 00:30:50.390
and why I do what I do.

00:30:50.390 --> 00:30:53.450
And I mean, it was a really
beautiful experience.

00:30:53.450 --> 00:30:56.621
And then she's
like, OK, it's over.

00:30:56.621 --> 00:30:58.870
And then she's like, I'm
going to bring the "LA Times"

00:30:58.870 --> 00:30:59.411
photographer.

00:30:59.411 --> 00:31:01.030
I'm like, what?

00:31:01.030 --> 00:31:02.110
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Oh, so you
didn't know the whole time

00:31:02.110 --> 00:31:03.000
it was for "LA Times?"

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:04.450
MANUEL LOPEZ: Well, I knew
it was from the "LA Times."

00:31:04.450 --> 00:31:06.990
But I didn't know that they
were going to be shooting.

00:31:06.990 --> 00:31:08.990
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Oh,
and when was this?

00:31:08.990 --> 00:31:10.300
MANUEL LOPEZ: This was
a couple of months ago.

00:31:10.300 --> 00:31:10.670
I think April.

00:31:10.670 --> 00:31:11.670
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Oh,
this was very recent.

00:31:11.670 --> 00:31:12.910
MANUEL LOPEZ: April, yeah.

00:31:12.910 --> 00:31:13.840
MARCUS GRIMALDO: That's awesome.

00:31:13.840 --> 00:31:14.320
And it's out.

00:31:14.320 --> 00:31:14.920
This is public.

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:15.795
People can go online.

00:31:15.795 --> 00:31:18.670
MANUEL LOPEZ: Yeah, it's
on the "LA Times" link.

00:31:18.670 --> 00:31:20.980
And so she brings the
photographer over.

00:31:20.980 --> 00:31:25.454
And I'm like, dude, I'm going to
take you guys up to the hills.

00:31:25.454 --> 00:31:26.620
That's my natural landscape.

00:31:26.620 --> 00:31:27.490
You know?

00:31:27.490 --> 00:31:29.470
And so we take the
photographer up there.

00:31:29.470 --> 00:31:33.980
And he's setting up his
flashes and all that stuff.

00:31:33.980 --> 00:31:35.650
And he's like, all
right, just sit down.

00:31:35.650 --> 00:31:36.650
You know, do your thing.

00:31:36.650 --> 00:31:38.830
And then I start drawing.

00:31:38.830 --> 00:31:39.820
She's like behind me.

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:42.010
She's like still
asking me questions.

00:31:42.010 --> 00:31:44.350
And then the photographer,
after we're all done,

00:31:44.350 --> 00:31:47.110
