I used to live in Highland Park
and I used to go to preschool.

00:34:57.835 --> 00:35:01.520
The preschool was right
across from our house.

00:35:01.520 --> 00:35:04.384
And in preschool,
all we did was art.

00:35:04.384 --> 00:35:06.550
So I started drawing since
I was like, I don't know,

00:35:06.550 --> 00:35:07.216
three years old.

00:35:09.850 --> 00:35:11.500
Shortly after that,
my mom started

00:35:11.500 --> 00:35:15.175
studying with a religious
group that's very--

00:35:15.175 --> 00:35:19.150
I don't want to say
the name of the group.

00:35:19.150 --> 00:35:20.810
I don't want to offend anyone.

00:35:20.810 --> 00:35:24.040
But it's a very difficult
religion to be a part of.

00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:28.760
Due to that, my dad sent us
to Mexico to their small town.

00:35:28.760 --> 00:35:30.970
It's called [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:30.970 --> 00:35:34.570
Back in '79, I don't know,
maybe a couple hundred people

00:35:34.570 --> 00:35:35.330
lived there.

00:35:35.330 --> 00:35:37.570
And that's where both
my parents are from.

00:35:37.570 --> 00:35:42.220
So he sent us there with
the intention of the family

00:35:42.220 --> 00:35:45.520
to turn my mom and
my sisters and myself

00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:48.010
back to being Catholic.

00:35:48.010 --> 00:35:51.460
We were the only ones
from that religion there.

00:35:51.460 --> 00:35:53.410
But instead of that
happening, my mom

00:35:53.410 --> 00:35:55.915
became a stronger
member of that religion.

00:35:58.470 --> 00:36:02.320
So we were in Mexico
from '79 to '89.

00:36:02.320 --> 00:36:05.110
During that time, being
part of that religion,

00:36:05.110 --> 00:36:07.210
you're not allowed to
associate or hang out

00:36:07.210 --> 00:36:10.120
with anyone else that's
not part of that religion.

00:36:10.120 --> 00:36:11.870
So I really had no friends.

00:36:11.870 --> 00:36:14.215
So my only friend
really was me drawing.

00:36:14.215 --> 00:36:17.860
I would just lock myself up
and draw, and draw all day.

00:36:17.860 --> 00:36:20.220
And so that's most of
what I did in Mexico,

00:36:20.220 --> 00:36:22.390
and be part of that religion.

00:36:22.390 --> 00:36:24.490
I mean, I was running
congregations when I was,

00:36:24.490 --> 00:36:26.960
like, 15 years old.

00:36:26.960 --> 00:36:30.610
So it's now '89.

00:36:30.610 --> 00:36:32.350
We came back to the States.

00:36:32.350 --> 00:36:36.730
And we weren't supposed
to come back and stay.

00:36:36.730 --> 00:36:38.924
My mom just one day
told my dad, you know,

00:36:38.924 --> 00:36:40.340
we're going to
come and visit you.

00:36:40.340 --> 00:36:42.100
And I was supposed
to stay in Mexico.

00:36:42.100 --> 00:36:44.270
But then everyone started
crying the night before.

00:36:44.270 --> 00:36:47.170
And then everyone's like,
all right, pack your stuff.

00:36:47.170 --> 00:36:48.950
We're going to take you with us.

00:36:48.950 --> 00:36:50.050
So we came here.

00:36:50.050 --> 00:36:52.330
And we ended up just staying.

00:36:52.330 --> 00:36:56.350
So shortly after that,
right out of high school,

00:36:56.350 --> 00:37:01.150
I got hired by Disney in
a very small department,

00:37:01.150 --> 00:37:04.330
a department that
was started back

00:37:04.330 --> 00:37:06.400
in the '20s by Walt Disney.

00:37:06.400 --> 00:37:09.580
And that department was
all women back then.

00:37:09.580 --> 00:37:10.125
And so--

00:37:10.125 --> 00:37:11.990
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Oh,
that's different.

00:37:11.990 --> 00:37:12.170
ANTONIO PELAYO: Yeah.

00:37:12.170 --> 00:37:12.730
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Right?

00:37:12.730 --> 00:37:13.980
ANTONIO PELAYO: It's so weird.

00:37:13.980 --> 00:37:17.530
Because I don't know.

00:37:17.530 --> 00:37:20.890
The department's going
to turn 100 in 2023.

00:37:20.890 --> 00:37:24.707
Forward to today, now
that department's all men.

00:37:24.707 --> 00:37:25.540
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Oh.

00:37:25.540 --> 00:37:29.150
ANTONIO PELAYO: Yeah, they just
hired my son about a year ago.

00:37:29.150 --> 00:37:30.774
And then we hired
another gentleman.

00:37:30.774 --> 00:37:33.190
MARCUS GRIMALDO: And that's
the ink and paint department--

00:37:33.190 --> 00:37:34.030
ANTONIO PELAYO: Ink and
paint department, yeah.

00:37:34.030 --> 00:37:34.960
MARCUS GRIMALDO: --you were
just talking about, right?

00:37:34.960 --> 00:37:35.620
ANTONIO PELAYO: Yeah.

00:37:35.620 --> 00:37:37.600
MARCUS GRIMALDO: For us,
again, we're not artists here.

00:37:37.600 --> 00:37:38.610
Well, I'm not definitely.

00:37:38.610 --> 00:37:40.610
And I don't know if anybody
else in the audience is.

00:37:40.610 --> 00:37:41.470
But I'm definitely
not an artist.

00:37:41.470 --> 00:37:43.600
I would like to know
well, what does that mean?

00:37:43.600 --> 00:37:46.720
Because I look at your paintings
just off of your website,

00:37:46.720 --> 00:37:49.739
for example, and it's
so different than what

00:37:49.739 --> 00:37:50.530
I'm used to seeing.

00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:51.029
Right?

00:37:53.650 --> 00:37:55.664
Talk to me about that,
ink and paint department.

00:37:55.664 --> 00:37:57.580
ANTONIO PELAYO: Well,
the inking and painting,

00:37:57.580 --> 00:37:58.900
I don't exhibit that.

00:37:58.900 --> 00:38:00.350
That's just what
I do for Disney.

00:38:00.350 --> 00:38:01.350
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Oh, OK.

00:38:01.350 --> 00:38:03.740
ANTONIO PELAYO: My
personal stuff is pencil.

00:38:03.740 --> 00:38:06.070
And this piece in
particular is not pencil.

00:38:06.070 --> 00:38:08.500
But it's from my pencil drawing.

00:38:08.500 --> 00:38:12.334
It's a collaboration I
did with Richard Duardo.

00:38:12.334 --> 00:38:13.500
MARCUS GRIMALDO: I saw that.

00:38:13.500 --> 00:38:15.010
ANTONIO PELAYO: So
that's his touch there.

00:38:15.010 --> 00:38:16.340
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Yeah,
this is your collaboration.

00:38:16.340 --> 00:38:16.839
OK, good.

00:38:16.839 --> 00:38:19.290
Because I saw the pencil art
that you have on your website

00:38:19.290 --> 00:38:20.079
for this.

00:38:20.079 --> 00:38:21.120
And then we saw this one.

00:38:21.120 --> 00:38:22.244
And I was researching this.

00:38:22.244 --> 00:38:23.610
It's a collaboration piece.

00:38:23.610 --> 00:38:29.440
As an artist, is it different
being in a collaboration piece?

00:38:29.440 --> 00:38:31.800
Because it seems when you
have your own artistry,

00:38:31.800 --> 00:38:33.370
it's very individualistic.

00:38:33.370 --> 00:38:35.700
It's very like, no,
this is like my story.

00:38:35.700 --> 00:38:36.400
I'm proud of it.

00:38:36.400 --> 00:38:40.217
It's not like you're
not segregating yourself

00:38:40.217 --> 00:38:41.800
from somebody because
of your beliefs.

00:38:41.800 --> 00:38:43.341
But you're just
proud of what you do.

00:38:43.341 --> 00:38:46.440
So how was this experience being
that it was a collaboration

00:38:46.440 --> 00:38:49.830
piece, and being an artist?

00:38:49.830 --> 00:38:52.440
ANTONIO PELAYO: Well,
Richard saw my work.

00:38:52.440 --> 00:38:54.940
And he said, we need
to do a collaboration.

00:38:54.940 --> 00:38:57.330
So I told him, well, what piece?

00:38:57.330 --> 00:38:58.590
I'll let you choose the piece.

00:38:58.590 --> 00:39:00.540
And he chose Frida.

00:39:00.540 --> 00:39:04.540
So I mean, I think that
collaboration was a lot of fun.

00:39:04.540 --> 00:39:05.820
I admire Richard.

00:39:05.820 --> 00:39:09.712
He became one of my mentors.

00:39:09.712 --> 00:39:10.920
MARCUS GRIMALDO: That's good.

00:39:10.920 --> 00:39:11.770
So nothing changed.

00:39:11.770 --> 00:39:12.270
That's good.

00:39:12.270 --> 00:39:13.440
Because, you know,
sometimes you collaborate.

00:39:13.440 --> 00:39:15.050
And it doesn't always--

00:39:15.050 --> 00:39:16.860
it doesn't always end
with a mentorship.

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:17.100
Right?

00:39:17.100 --> 00:39:17.400
ANTONIO PELAYO: Yeah.

00:39:17.400 --> 00:39:18.180
MARCUS GRIMALDO:
So that's awesome.

00:39:18.180 --> 00:39:19.380
ANTONIO PELAYO: No,
Richard was awesome.

00:39:19.380 --> 00:39:20.220
MARCUS GRIMALDO: OK.

00:39:20.220 --> 00:39:22.984
And why did he choose
the Frida Kahlo?

00:39:22.984 --> 00:39:24.900
ANTONIO PELAYO: Probably
because of, you know,

00:39:24.900 --> 00:39:27.660
she's such an iconic,
just like Selena.

00:39:27.660 --> 00:39:32.250
And she's inspired a
lot of us as artists.

00:39:32.250 --> 00:39:33.990
She was one of my
inspirations growing up

00:39:33.990 --> 00:39:38.890
in Mexico, her, Diego, all
the muralists from Mexico.

00:39:38.890 --> 00:39:39.390
Yeah.

00:39:39.390 --> 00:39:40.723
MARCUS GRIMALDO: That's awesome.

00:39:40.723 --> 00:39:42.889
And what's the next
big thing for you?

00:39:42.889 --> 00:39:44.430
Are you working on
anything right now

00:39:44.430 --> 00:39:45.960
that we should be aware of?

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:46.961
Are you still at Disney?

00:39:46.961 --> 00:39:48.876
Is there something new
that you're trying out?

00:39:48.876 --> 00:39:51.030
Is there more collaborations
that we should expect?

00:39:51.030 --> 00:39:53.550
ANTONIO PELAYO: Still at Disney.

00:39:53.550 --> 00:39:58.200
Currently, I'm working to
expand my Familia series.

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:01.860
And it was a documentation of my
family's migration from Mexico.

00:40:01.860 --> 00:40:03.840
I have a part one
and part two on that.

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:06.510
And I plan on expanding on that.

00:40:06.510 --> 00:40:11.280
And also, I do some
lucha libre pieces

00:40:11.280 --> 00:40:12.447
that I'm experimenting with.

00:40:12.447 --> 00:40:13.863
MARCUS GRIMALDO:
That's fantastic.

00:40:13.863 --> 00:40:16.470
So I'm going to lead us into
the theme, as I mentioned--

00:40:16.470 --> 00:40:17.100
[SPANISH]

00:40:17.100 --> 00:40:17.380
Right?

00:40:17.380 --> 00:40:19.620
That's kind of where we're
at with Hispanic Heritage

00:40:19.620 --> 00:40:23.310
Month and the theme that we want
to convey throughout Hispanic

00:40:23.310 --> 00:40:24.240
Heritage Month.

00:40:24.240 --> 00:40:26.850
So when you look
at your artwork,

00:40:26.850 --> 00:40:29.040
if you had to choose
one of your paintings

00:40:29.040 --> 00:40:32.130
or your artistic expressions--

00:40:32.130 --> 00:40:34.000
I don't want to say
the wrong words here--

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:35.760
but if you had to
choose one thing that

00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:39.300
would be representative of
that, what would it be and why?

00:40:39.300 --> 00:40:42.310
And what does that mean to you?

00:40:42.310 --> 00:40:46.110
ANTONIO PELAYO: For me, I
think, from Mi Familia series.

00:40:46.110 --> 00:40:48.090
I mean, I would say all of them.

00:40:48.090 --> 00:40:49.920
But one in particular
would probably

00:40:49.920 --> 00:40:56.130
be a portrait of my
dad and his cousin.

00:40:56.130 --> 00:40:58.860
And I got it from a
photo that they took.

00:40:58.860 --> 00:41:04.320
And it was taken the day
they got deported from LA.

00:41:04.320 --> 00:41:06.340
And it was a photo
taken in Mexico.

00:41:06.340 --> 00:41:08.460
So I drew that.

00:41:08.460 --> 00:41:13.680
So that, to me, you
know, meant a lot.

00:41:13.680 --> 00:41:16.890
I can relate in some ways
because I migrated to Mexico.

00:41:16.890 --> 00:41:19.210
And then I migrated back here.

00:41:19.210 --> 00:41:23.040
And I wanted--

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:26.770
I wanted to play
with that message

00:41:26.770 --> 00:41:30.360
and to show people
like the things

00:41:30.360 --> 00:41:33.750
that we go through
as immigrants, things

00:41:33.750 --> 00:41:37.984
that we feel, like feeling
lost in another country.

00:41:37.984 --> 00:41:39.900
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Yeah,
I was going to ask you.

00:41:39.900 --> 00:41:43.110
That must have had a profound
effect on you, being so young

00:41:43.110 --> 00:41:44.900
and going through
that experience.

00:41:44.900 --> 00:41:47.489
I mean, I hate
moving myself now.

00:41:47.489 --> 00:41:49.530
I can't even imagine what
it would have been like

00:41:49.530 --> 00:41:50.970
as a child, right?

00:41:50.970 --> 00:41:54.360
ANTONIO PELAYO: Well, imagine
going to your hometown

00:41:54.360 --> 00:41:59.010
and no one there likes
you because you're not

00:41:59.010 --> 00:42:02.040
part of their religion.

00:42:02.040 --> 00:42:04.830
And then coming back here,
I lost all the friends

00:42:04.830 --> 00:42:05.940
that I had.

00:42:05.940 --> 00:42:08.059
So I had no friends here.

00:42:08.059 --> 00:42:08.850
I'm in high school.

00:42:08.850 --> 00:42:11.890
And I hated school
for those reasons.

00:42:11.890 --> 00:42:14.010
And when I came back
here, my English was shot.

00:42:14.010 --> 00:42:19.674
So they put me in ESL for
about a year until I caught up.

00:42:19.674 --> 00:42:21.840
MARCUS GRIMALDO: So imagination
was your best friend

00:42:21.840 --> 00:42:22.510
and the pencil.

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:23.830
ANTONIO PELAYO:
Pretty much, yeah.

00:42:23.830 --> 00:42:24.230
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Awesome.

00:42:24.230 --> 00:42:25.724
Thank you for sharing.

00:42:25.724 --> 00:42:28.060
Margaret?

00:42:28.060 --> 00:42:28.680
[SPANISH]

00:42:28.680 --> 00:42:29.380
MARGARET GARCIA: [SPANISH].

00:42:29.380 --> 00:42:31.130
MARCUS GRIMALDO: What
does it mean to you?

00:42:31.130 --> 00:42:34.150
What painting, or
expression, or artistic--

00:42:34.150 --> 00:42:36.490
I mean, you gave
us a great intro,

00:42:36.490 --> 00:42:40.750
a lot of strong themes here
that were very close to us, just

00:42:40.750 --> 00:42:42.190
being [INAUDIBLE] in general.

00:42:42.190 --> 00:42:44.320
What would be your answer
to that question, as far

00:42:44.320 --> 00:42:48.940
as the theme that we're trying
to convey here and your art?

00:42:48.940 --> 00:42:50.680
MARGARET GARCIA:
The public artwork

00:42:50.680 --> 00:42:54.550
that I did for the Universal
Studios metro station.

00:42:54.550 --> 00:42:58.885
Because it covers the
history of the Mexicano here

00:42:58.885 --> 00:43:02.050
and in California,
and how California

00:43:02.050 --> 00:43:04.870
became a part of
the United States,

00:43:04.870 --> 00:43:07.720
and how it was part of Mexico.

00:43:07.720 --> 00:43:11.470
And I worked on that
particular project--

00:43:11.470 --> 00:43:15.860
I mean, from beginning to end,
it was a span of 10 years.

00:43:15.860 --> 00:43:19.240
And I had a
historian, Bill Mason,

00:43:19.240 --> 00:43:23.200
who worked for the Museum of
Natural History, who provided

00:43:23.200 --> 00:43:27.400
me with a lot of the research in
order to get that history down.

00:43:27.400 --> 00:43:31.960
And it covers that
period of history.

00:43:31.960 --> 00:43:34.790
So I would have to go with that.

00:43:34.790 --> 00:43:39.301
But other than that, I would
have to say my next painting.

00:43:39.301 --> 00:43:41.410
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Uh
oh, I like that, next.

00:43:41.410 --> 00:43:43.260
And how do we--

00:43:43.260 --> 00:43:45.040
can you give us some kind of--

00:43:45.040 --> 00:43:47.200
MARGARET GARCIA: I'm
expected to do a solo show

00:43:47.200 --> 00:43:49.900
at the Museum of Ventura--

00:43:49.900 --> 00:43:55.720
in the Ventura Museum of
Art in 2020, in the fall.

00:43:55.720 --> 00:43:57.040
MARCUS GRIMALDO: OK, all right.

00:43:57.040 --> 00:44:00.390
Well, we've got to stay
updated and stay close to that

00:44:00.390 --> 00:44:01.975
because that's very exciting.

00:44:01.975 --> 00:44:03.100
So congratulations on that.

00:44:03.100 --> 00:44:04.900
And we can't wait
for that to happen.

00:44:04.900 --> 00:44:06.480
MARGARET GARCIA: Thank you.

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:10.422
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Sir, your turn.

00:44:10.422 --> 00:44:12.284
MANUEL LOPEZ: Favorite piece?

00:44:12.284 --> 00:44:14.200
MARCUS GRIMALDO: Favorite
piece in the context

00:44:14.200 --> 00:44:18.330
of like [SPANISH],, hear me,
what that means for you.

00:44:18.330 --> 00:44:20.740
Again, it could be
a political sense.

00:44:20.740 --> 00:44:24.040
It could be just
a personal stance.

00:44:24.040 --> 00:44:25.720
It could be motivational.

00:44:25.720 --> 00:44:29.079
I mean, I don't want to get to--

00:44:29.079 --> 00:44:30.370
make it a contract or anything.

00:44:30.370 --> 00:44:33.580
But I'd like to know if,
you know, given where we're

00:44:33.580 --> 00:44:37.401
at with hear me, [SPANISH],,
and the state of where we're

00:44:37.401 --> 00:44:37.900
at today.

00:44:37.900 --> 00:44:38.800
You've heard the stories.

00:44:38.800 --> 00:44:39.799
You have your narrative.

00:44:39.799 --> 00:44:41.650
If you had to
choose one painting,

00:44:41.650 --> 00:44:44.776
or artistic expression,
that you have,

00:44:44.776 --> 00:44:45.900
what would that be and why?

00:44:49.340 --> 00:44:52.190
MANUEL LOPEZ: I did what
is it, like a dictionary

00:44:52.190 --> 00:44:54.552
back in second
grade, where we did

00:44:54.552 --> 00:44:55.760
every letter in the alphabet.

00:44:55.760 --> 00:45:00.110
And then we had to pick like
nine drawings for each letter.

00:45:00.110 --> 00:45:03.590
And my mom just barely found
it a couple of months ago.

00:45:03.590 --> 00:45:05.480
And we sat down.

00:45:05.480 --> 00:45:06.650
And we just went through it.

00:45:06.650 --> 00:45:11.210
And I mean, I think
that was pretty special

00:45:11.210 --> 00:45:14.400
because you're being
introduced through a language.

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:18.160
Like, I feel like
my English is very--

00:45:18.160 --> 00:45:19.880
it's not-- I mean,
I was born here.

00:45:19.880 --> 00:45:22.070
But I grew up as
a Spanish speaker

00:45:22.070 --> 00:45:23.970
so I still have that
very heavy accent.

00:45:23.970 --> 00:45:27.890
And I'm just going
through the alphabet

00:45:27.890 --> 00:45:29.150
in the English language.

00:45:29.150 --> 00:45:32.130
And I threw in a bunch of like--

00:45:32.130 --> 00:45:33.530
I threw in some
nopales in there.

00:45:33.530 --> 00:45:35.300
I threw in some [SPANISH].

00:45:35.300 --> 00:45:38.000
So just to know that you
could interplay, you know,

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:42.950
the cultures, and to know
that it's OK to do that.

00:45:42.950 --> 00:45:44.589
You know, I thought that was--

00:45:44.589 --> 00:45:46.130
I mean, just in
retrospect, you know,

00:45:46.130 --> 00:45:50.360
seeing that a couple of months
ago, and it makes it OK.

00:45:50.360 --> 00:45:54.140
And I just was just really happy
that my mom took care of it

00:45:54.140 --> 00:45:57.210
after all these years.

00:45:57.210 --> 00:45:59.660
Yeah, I think that one
definitely probably speaks--

00:45:59.660 --> 00:46:04.700
